00:32:57.120 --> 00:33:00.360
into just opening up the
Q&amp;A with a couple thoughts

00:33:00.360 --> 00:33:03.010
that I have, having
watched this book

00:33:03.010 --> 00:33:05.650
come together over the
past three to five years

00:33:05.650 --> 00:33:07.150
and watched Derek's
career progress.

00:33:07.150 --> 00:33:08.160
So I'll kick things off.

00:33:08.160 --> 00:33:09.550
And then in the
interest of time,

00:33:09.550 --> 00:33:11.230
we'll open things up
to any of you guys

00:33:11.230 --> 00:33:12.660
that would like
to ask a question.

00:33:12.660 --> 00:33:18.160
And if you would, go to the mics
for that, that would be great.

00:33:18.160 --> 00:33:21.550
So I had a bunch of things
I wanted to ask you.

00:33:21.550 --> 00:33:23.484
But one of the central
figures of the book

00:33:23.484 --> 00:33:25.150
that you talk about
that I learned about

00:33:25.150 --> 00:33:26.660
for the first time--

00:33:26.660 --> 00:33:29.560
is fascinating--
was Raymond Loewy

00:33:29.560 --> 00:33:32.710
and would love to hear
how you discovered him

00:33:32.710 --> 00:33:36.520
and how his theories of design
relate to some of the topics

00:33:36.520 --> 00:33:37.295
that you bring up.

00:33:37.295 --> 00:33:38.170
DEREK THOMPSON: Yeah.

00:33:38.170 --> 00:33:41.590
I discovered Raymond
Loewy on just one

00:33:41.590 --> 00:33:47.320
of those weird Wikipedia rabbit
holes, just opening new tab,

00:33:47.320 --> 00:33:49.630
new tab, new tab, new tab.

00:33:49.630 --> 00:33:54.610
And this is someone who you
either have heard of him

00:33:54.610 --> 00:33:58.240
and you revere him more
than almost anyone you know,

00:33:58.240 --> 00:34:00.060
or you haven't heard of him.

00:34:00.060 --> 00:34:02.470
And the vast majority of
people that I have encountered

00:34:02.470 --> 00:34:03.370
have not.

00:34:03.370 --> 00:34:05.830
Raymond Loewy is the father
of industrial design.

00:34:05.830 --> 00:34:10.739
He is a French orphan who came
over to the US the 19-teens.

00:34:10.739 --> 00:34:13.690
In the 1940s and
1950s, designed what

00:34:13.690 --> 00:34:16.060
we've come to think of
as mid-century America.

00:34:16.060 --> 00:34:19.929
Imagine Don Draper, a
genius of human psychology,

00:34:19.929 --> 00:34:22.960
meeting Steve Jobs,
a genius of design,

00:34:22.960 --> 00:34:25.040
coming together, having a baby.

00:34:25.040 --> 00:34:26.500
That baby is Raymond Loewy.

00:34:26.500 --> 00:34:30.520
This guy designed the
1950s Studebaker coupe,

00:34:30.520 --> 00:34:33.070
one of the famous automotive
designs of the 20th century.

00:34:33.070 --> 00:34:36.429
He designed the modern train
for Pennsylvania Railroad.

00:34:36.429 --> 00:34:37.908
He designed the modern tractor.

00:34:37.908 --> 00:34:39.449
He designed the
pencil sharpener that

00:34:39.449 --> 00:34:42.730
looks like an egg with a spindle
that you guys have surely seen.

00:34:42.730 --> 00:34:47.020
He designed the logos
for Exxon, Shell, and BP.

00:34:47.020 --> 00:34:49.360
He designed the
Lucky Strike package,

00:34:49.360 --> 00:34:53.580
made famously ironic
by Madmen itself.

00:34:53.580 --> 00:34:58.030
When NASA was making
its first spaceship,

00:34:58.030 --> 00:35:01.639
they asked Raymond Loewy to
design its interior habitat,

00:35:01.639 --> 00:35:03.430
because he was this
genius in understanding

00:35:03.430 --> 00:35:05.500
what people wanted.

00:35:05.500 --> 00:35:11.290
And it was his idea to
install the viewing portal.

00:35:11.290 --> 00:35:14.021
So every time in a movie,
when you're in outer space

00:35:14.021 --> 00:35:15.520
and you can look
through that window

00:35:15.520 --> 00:35:17.274
back at the pale
blue Earth, that

00:35:17.274 --> 00:35:18.940
is Raymond Loewy that
you're looking at.

00:35:18.940 --> 00:35:21.490
It was his idea to put
a window in a spaceship.

00:35:21.490 --> 00:35:24.137
So the great question
for anybody, I think,

00:35:24.137 --> 00:35:25.720
who understands
Raymond Loewy's career

00:35:25.720 --> 00:35:28.150
is, how the heck did this
guy know what people liked,

00:35:28.150 --> 00:35:30.670
from pencil sharpeners
to spaceships?

00:35:30.670 --> 00:35:35.020
And his theory was
called MAYA, M-A-Y-A--

00:35:35.020 --> 00:35:38.680
Most Advanced Yet Acceptable.

00:35:38.680 --> 00:35:41.950
And it was his thesis
that every consumer is

00:35:41.950 --> 00:35:43.690
torn between opposing forces.

00:35:43.690 --> 00:35:49.940
Neophilia, a love of new things,
a need to discover new things--

00:35:49.940 --> 00:35:51.940
sorry, neophilia,
love of new things,

00:35:51.940 --> 00:35:55.900
and neophobia, a deep fear
of anything that is too new.

00:35:55.900 --> 00:35:57.790
And he was just
absolutely brilliant

00:35:57.790 --> 00:36:01.270
at using anthropology to
study consumers and understand

00:36:01.270 --> 00:36:04.200
their habits and understand
exactly how they live

00:36:04.200 --> 00:36:06.700
and then build new products
that essentially piggybacked off

00:36:06.700 --> 00:36:07.570
of them.

00:36:07.570 --> 00:36:09.150
And so again, this
concept of MAYA

00:36:09.150 --> 00:36:11.680
and familiar surprises
just so beautifully

00:36:11.680 --> 00:36:14.680
clicks into Hollywood's
franchise strategy,

00:36:14.680 --> 00:36:19.090
ESPN SportsCenter strategy,
the strategy of Buzzfeed

00:36:19.090 --> 00:36:21.520
for creating shareable
videos, and just

00:36:21.520 --> 00:36:24.100
across the entertainment
and media landscape--

00:36:24.100 --> 00:36:26.710
this power of familiar
surprises and MAYA,

00:36:26.710 --> 00:36:28.100
for giving people
what they want.

00:36:28.100 --> 00:36:29.600
MICHAEL: That's
interesting to think

00:36:29.600 --> 00:36:32.079
about how that relates to
some of the big tech companies

00:36:32.079 --> 00:36:34.120
and how we release products
all the time as well.

00:36:34.120 --> 00:36:34.430
DEREK THOMPSON: Right.

00:36:34.430 --> 00:36:36.410
And so one of the
ways I summarize

00:36:36.410 --> 00:36:40.390
MAYA is I say, to sell something
surprising, make it familiar.

00:36:40.390 --> 00:36:43.700
But to sell something
familiar, make it surprising.

00:36:43.700 --> 00:36:45.380
And so in technology,
the challenge

00:36:45.380 --> 00:36:49.710
is often how to make something
that is surprising familiar.

00:36:49.710 --> 00:36:52.490
But the best technologists
do this all the time.

00:36:52.490 --> 00:36:54.836
When Steve Jobs was designing
one of the first Macs,

00:36:54.836 --> 00:36:56.210
there's that famous
line that you

00:36:56.210 --> 00:36:58.850
see Michael Fassbender say
in the movie "Steve Jobs"

00:36:58.850 --> 00:37:01.680
where he's looking at the
computer and he says--

00:37:01.680 --> 00:37:04.460
at the monitor and he says,
it has to look like a face.

00:37:04.460 --> 00:37:07.160
It has to literally say hello.

00:37:07.160 --> 00:37:09.110
To sell a new
consumer product, he

00:37:09.110 --> 00:37:10.910
had to make it
seem like a friend.

00:37:10.910 --> 00:37:13.460
The modern incarnation
of that is clearly Alexa.

00:37:13.460 --> 00:37:15.950
It is the hottest
new technology, AI.

00:37:15.950 --> 00:37:17.055
How do how do we use it?

00:37:17.055 --> 00:37:18.180
How do we interact with it?

00:37:18.180 --> 00:37:21.110
It's incredibly new
and potentially scary.

00:37:21.110 --> 00:37:23.420
But Alexis sounds
like a lilting woman.

00:37:23.420 --> 00:37:26.030
It sounds like an
ordinary assistant.

00:37:26.030 --> 00:37:27.710
It sounds like a kind friend.

00:37:27.710 --> 00:37:29.210
And so again, to
sell something that

00:37:29.210 --> 00:37:31.370
is inherently surprising
and confusing,

00:37:31.370 --> 00:37:33.500
the challenge and
ultimate success

00:37:33.500 --> 00:37:37.099
is often in those who can
make it really familiar.

00:37:37.099 --> 00:37:38.140
MICHAEL: Thanks for that.

00:37:38.140 --> 00:37:40.450
I think with the
Google audience,

00:37:40.450 --> 00:37:42.900
I think we're constantly
aware of the rise of big data

00:37:42.900 --> 00:37:45.030
and machine learning
and algorithms,

00:37:45.030 --> 00:37:46.590
helping us predict things.

00:37:46.590 --> 00:37:51.150
How do you think that big
data and machine learning play

00:37:51.150 --> 00:37:54.300
in with the ability to
predict hits potentially?

00:37:54.300 --> 00:37:57.420
DEREK THOMPSON: So I think that
every media and entertainment

00:37:57.420 --> 00:38:01.060
company is trying to
get into big data.

00:38:01.060 --> 00:38:06.510
And I think that the results
have been disappointing

00:38:06.510 --> 00:38:08.690
for the following reason.

00:38:08.690 --> 00:38:10.700
I think that when
a company, trying

00:38:10.700 --> 00:38:15.440
to discover human
tastes, uses or begins

00:38:15.440 --> 00:38:18.470
to use a new technology
to uncover them,

00:38:18.470 --> 00:38:20.700
they want to learn
something new.

00:38:20.700 --> 00:38:23.480
They want to learn something
that's counterintuitive.

00:38:23.480 --> 00:38:26.210
And I think that
what seems to me

00:38:26.210 --> 00:38:29.330
to have happened in the music
and movie industry specifically

00:38:29.330 --> 00:38:31.940
is that the smarter these
industries have gotten

00:38:31.940 --> 00:38:35.210
at discerning audience
tastes, the more it

00:38:35.210 --> 00:38:40.630
turns out that audience tastes
are incredibly derivative.

00:38:40.630 --> 00:38:44.310
Pop music now is more
repetitive than it used to be.

00:38:44.310 --> 00:38:46.219
Hollywood sequels
are a bigger part

00:38:46.219 --> 00:38:47.760
of the business than
they used to be.

00:38:47.760 --> 00:38:50.670
In 1996, none of
the top 10 films--

00:38:50.670 --> 00:38:52.860
"Independence Day," "Twister,"
"First Wives Club"--

00:38:52.860 --> 00:38:56.490
none of the top 10 films
were adaptations, sequels,

00:38:56.490 --> 00:38:57.120
or reboots.

00:38:57.120 --> 00:38:58.710
None of them were
comic book movies.

00:38:58.710 --> 00:39:05.040
20 years later, by 2016,
every year this century,

00:39:05.040 --> 00:39:08.130
a majority of the top
10 films in the US

00:39:08.130 --> 00:39:10.170
have been sequels,
adaptations, and reboots.

00:39:10.170 --> 00:39:12.060
As the industry
has gotten smarter,

00:39:12.060 --> 00:39:14.140
the product has become
more derivative.

00:39:14.140 --> 00:39:17.594
And so the irony here is that
the use of big data seems

00:39:17.594 --> 00:39:20.010
to me-- this is my read, and
other people might definitely

00:39:20.010 --> 00:39:25.410
disagree-- but my read of it is
that the employment of this new

00:39:25.410 --> 00:39:30.300
technology has ironically
taught hit makers and cultural

00:39:30.300 --> 00:39:32.610
producers the first lesson--

00:39:32.610 --> 00:39:34.620
literally, the first lesson--

00:39:34.620 --> 00:39:37.470
of human psychology, which
was probably the mere exposure

00:39:37.470 --> 00:39:38.250
effect--

00:39:38.250 --> 00:39:41.010
the idea that the mere
exposure of a stimulus

00:39:41.010 --> 00:39:44.430
to us over and over and
over again biases us

00:39:44.430 --> 00:39:45.960
toward that stimulus--

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:48.480
that we have a strong
preference for the familiar,

00:39:48.480 --> 00:39:50.400
specifically when
we can't see where

00:39:50.400 --> 00:39:53.760
that stimulus is coming from,
when it's sort of furtive.

00:39:53.760 --> 00:39:56.760
So first discovery in
psychology history--

00:39:56.760 --> 00:39:58.440
familiarity breeds liking.

00:39:58.440 --> 00:40:01.170
Last discovery of this
whip-smart new technology--

00:40:01.170 --> 00:40:02.450
familiarity breeds liking.

00:40:02.450 --> 00:40:04.450
And I think that for a
lot of culture producers,

00:40:04.450 --> 00:40:06.632
that's been a
disappointing finding.

00:40:06.632 --> 00:40:08.490
MICHAEL: Well, thank you, Derek.

00:40:08.490 --> 00:40:11.480
I want to open it up to
questions from the audience.

00:40:11.480 --> 00:40:12.600
AUDIENCE: Hi, Derek.

00:40:12.600 --> 00:40:14.030
Thank you very much.

00:40:14.030 --> 00:40:17.460
I have a question about the
very first-- sorry, I'm cold.

00:40:17.460 --> 00:40:20.140
So that's why I
have my big jacket.

00:40:20.140 --> 00:40:22.370
I have a question about
the very first iPhone.

00:40:22.370 --> 00:40:28.080
I'd like to know your point of
view on how it fits in this not

00:40:28.080 --> 00:40:31.520
too new-- like people prefer
familiarity over novelty--

00:40:31.520 --> 00:40:35.780
because to me, and I might be
wrong, it was very, very new,

00:40:35.780 --> 00:40:38.810
this first concept with
application, smartphone,

00:40:38.810 --> 00:40:40.010
and everything.

00:40:40.010 --> 00:40:42.070
And yet, it was a big success.

00:40:42.070 --> 00:40:45.560
So did they compensate
with distribution?

00:40:45.560 --> 00:40:49.540
How would you
position the iPhone?

00:40:49.540 --> 00:40:52.543
DEREK THOMPSON: So if
you turn to page 231--

00:40:52.543 --> 00:40:53.919
AUDIENCE: I didn't
read the book.

00:40:53.919 --> 00:40:54.918
DEREK THOMPSON: It's OK.

00:40:54.918 --> 00:40:56.350
There are books
right behind you.

00:40:56.350 --> 00:40:58.266
I actually tell the story
of the first iPhone.

00:40:58.266 --> 00:41:01.970
So just to briefly summarize
that which all of you

00:41:01.970 --> 00:41:06.680
can read, first of all,
I don't think the iPhone

00:41:06.680 --> 00:41:08.660
was all that new in look.

00:41:08.660 --> 00:41:13.810
In many ways, it was promised
as a wide-screen iPod--

00:41:13.810 --> 00:41:17.750
that essentially you could
think of the iPhone as sort

00:41:17.750 --> 00:41:21.170
of evolving almost
Darwinistically-- not a word,

00:41:21.170 --> 00:41:22.700
but we'll use it here--

00:41:22.700 --> 00:41:25.250
from the earliest
models of the iPod--

00:41:25.250 --> 00:41:29.345
that you had developed
a square with a screen.

00:41:29.345 --> 00:41:31.220
Then the screen got
bigger and bigger.

00:41:31.220 --> 00:41:33.410
And the dial got
smaller and smaller

00:41:33.410 --> 00:41:36.560
until it was ultimately all
touch with a single button.

00:41:36.560 --> 00:41:39.020
Here's the interesting thing
about the iPhone as a hit is

00:41:39.020 --> 00:41:45.020
that when Universal McCann,
the marketing company,

00:41:45.020 --> 00:41:47.840
did a 10,000-person poll all
over the world to ask people

00:41:47.840 --> 00:41:50.660
if they wanted the iPhone, not
only did most people in the US

00:41:50.660 --> 00:41:54.500
say they did not, because it
was an all-in-one device--

00:41:54.500 --> 00:41:56.475
it was a jack-of-all-trades,
master of none--

00:41:56.475 --> 00:41:58.100
that was the idea of
the first iPhone--

00:41:58.100 --> 00:42:00.440
all those jokes about how
the call quality is terrible,

00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:01.610
the internet's terrible.

00:42:01.610 --> 00:42:04.165
It's a cool new phone, but
it doesn't do anything well.

00:42:04.165 --> 00:42:05.540
They said, this
is actually going

00:42:05.540 --> 00:42:08.120
to be most popular in
developing countries

00:42:08.120 --> 00:42:10.280
where they don't already
have expensive cameras

00:42:10.280 --> 00:42:15.680
and expensive iPods and
expensive computers.

00:42:15.680 --> 00:42:20.180
And in many ways, what's
fascinating is how unbelievably

00:42:20.180 --> 00:42:21.590
wrong that prediction was--

00:42:21.590 --> 00:42:26.830
that the iPhone was only
supposed to work in Malaysia

00:42:26.830 --> 00:42:29.760
and was supposed to be uniquely
unpopular in Germany, Japan,

00:42:29.760 --> 00:42:30.530
and the US.

00:42:30.530 --> 00:42:32.060
And then Germany,
Japan, and the US

00:42:32.060 --> 00:42:35.552
ultimately served to
be its singular market.

00:42:35.552 --> 00:42:37.010
But as a matter
familiar surprises,

00:42:37.010 --> 00:42:40.070
I think that Jobs
introduced the iPhone--

00:42:40.070 --> 00:42:42.500
if it was his ultimate
goal to make the iPhones--

00:42:42.500 --> 00:42:43.790
a lot of people say it was--

00:42:43.790 --> 00:42:45.490
he introduced it brilliantly--

00:42:45.490 --> 00:42:47.570
that you don't go from 0 to 60.

00:42:47.570 --> 00:42:48.709
You introduce an iPod.

00:42:48.709 --> 00:42:50.750
And the screen gets bigger
and bigger and bigger.

00:42:50.750 --> 00:42:54.620
And you lead people
into the new product.

00:42:54.620 --> 00:42:58.010
So for many people, I think
they looked at the iPod itself

00:42:58.010 --> 00:43:02.330
and they said, oh, this is
the obvious next iteration

00:43:02.330 --> 00:43:03.038
of the iPod.

00:43:03.038 --> 00:43:06.530
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:06.530 --> 00:43:10.240
AUDIENCE: You had mentioned
earlier an increase in mistrust

00:43:10.240 --> 00:43:12.180
in the big established media.

00:43:12.180 --> 00:43:16.320
And assuming that we can
measure that and that it's true,

00:43:16.320 --> 00:43:18.120
what do you attribute that to?

00:43:18.120 --> 00:43:23.500
Big media still have
big distribution power.

00:43:23.500 --> 00:43:25.525
So what do you think
are the causes of that?

00:43:25.525 --> 00:43:28.150
DEREK THOMPSON: This is a really
good and complicated question.

00:43:28.150 --> 00:43:32.550
And in one way--

00:43:32.550 --> 00:43:34.530
so several things--
first, there's

00:43:34.530 --> 00:43:37.890
been macro, across
the board, collapse

00:43:37.890 --> 00:43:41.190
in trust since the
1960s, 1970s, not just

00:43:41.190 --> 00:43:43.050
for politics or Congress
or the White House,

00:43:43.050 --> 00:43:45.780
but basically across
all institutions.

00:43:45.780 --> 00:43:48.720
And the media, I think,
has been sort of brought

00:43:48.720 --> 00:43:52.476
into that undertow of distrust.

00:43:52.476 --> 00:43:53.850
But specifically,
what's happened

00:43:53.850 --> 00:43:57.120
to the press is that, as you've
had this sort of Cambrian

00:43:57.120 --> 00:44:01.710
explosion of media sources--

00:44:01.710 --> 00:44:06.870
first with the rise
of cable news and then

00:44:06.870 --> 00:44:10.460
with the rise of the internet--

00:44:10.460 --> 00:44:13.520
there are so many
news sources now

00:44:13.520 --> 00:44:16.550
that can appeal to
a specific niche

00:44:16.550 --> 00:44:19.580
that there is always a news
source that A, can tell you

00:44:19.580 --> 00:44:22.430
that that which you think
is already true, and B,

00:44:22.430 --> 00:44:25.880
can tell you that the
mainstream is wrong.

00:44:25.880 --> 00:44:28.910
And in sociology, this
is very, very similar

00:44:28.910 --> 00:44:33.320
to the technical
definition of culting.

00:44:33.320 --> 00:44:35.270
The sociological
definition of a cult

00:44:35.270 --> 00:44:39.860
is a positive rebellion
against the mainstream, which

00:44:39.860 --> 00:44:42.560
is ironically the same as
the cultural sociological

00:44:42.560 --> 00:44:45.230
definition of coolness,
which tells you something

00:44:45.230 --> 00:44:48.560
about the blurring of the lines
between coolness and culting--

00:44:48.560 --> 00:44:50.302
that cults are
essentially cool kids that

00:44:50.302 --> 00:44:52.010
are too far outside
the mainstream for us

00:44:52.010 --> 00:44:54.639
to accept them.

00:44:54.639 --> 00:44:56.180
But what's clearly
happened, I think,

00:44:56.180 --> 00:44:58.340
is that the abundance
of media sources

00:44:58.340 --> 00:45:01.250
have given rise to a kind of
media culting, in which case,

00:45:01.250 --> 00:45:02.990
you can always find
a media source that

00:45:02.990 --> 00:45:05.330
says that you're right and
the mainstream is wrong.

00:45:05.330 --> 00:45:08.056
This is clearly a
destroyed trust.

00:45:08.056 --> 00:45:09.680
But I think the last
thing to point out

00:45:09.680 --> 00:45:13.400
is that as you've had this
Cambrian explosion of media

00:45:13.400 --> 00:45:18.380
options, the media,
as a collective noun,

00:45:18.380 --> 00:45:22.280
no longer makes sense
to apply adjectives to.

00:45:22.280 --> 00:45:24.560
When people say, the
media is liberal,

00:45:24.560 --> 00:45:25.970
or the media is
too conservative,

00:45:25.970 --> 00:45:28.430
or the media's too
corporatist, it's like saying,

00:45:28.430 --> 00:45:31.690
food is too spicy, or
shirts are too blue.

00:45:31.690 --> 00:45:32.630
It's like, what?

00:45:32.630 --> 00:45:33.300
I don't know.

00:45:33.300 --> 00:45:37.130
Buy a non-blue shirt or don't
go to the Mexican place.

00:45:37.130 --> 00:45:40.670
There's so many options
on media right now

00:45:40.670 --> 00:45:43.300
that are diametrically
opposed to one another

00:45:43.300 --> 00:45:46.490
that I tend to resist any-- and
this wasn't your description.

00:45:46.490 --> 00:45:49.310
I'm just saying, I
tend to resist and sort

00:45:49.310 --> 00:45:54.230
of bristle at any suggestion
that the media is too blank.

00:45:54.230 --> 00:45:56.510
The real problem, I
think, is the opposite.

00:45:56.510 --> 00:45:58.460
The media is too big, maybe.

00:45:58.460 --> 00:46:00.800
There are so many sources
that it is inherently

00:46:00.800 --> 00:46:04.100
that we distrust
the mainstream Borg

00:46:04.100 --> 00:46:05.645
and just like our little cut.

00:46:11.367 --> 00:46:12.200
AUDIENCE: Hi, Derek.

00:46:12.200 --> 00:46:13.610
DEREK THOMPSON: Hi.

00:46:13.610 --> 00:46:16.000
AUDIENCE: I'm curious how
universal these principles are

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:17.800
over the course
of one's lifetime.

00:46:17.800 --> 00:46:21.804
Like I love Selena Gomez
maybe, but my grandmother

00:46:21.804 --> 00:46:22.720
may hate Selena Gomez.

00:46:22.720 --> 00:46:23.540
She doesn't like country.

00:46:23.540 --> 00:46:24.456
She doesn't like rock.

00:46:24.456 --> 00:46:26.630
She doesn't like pop,
doesn't like hip hop.

00:46:26.630 --> 00:46:28.245
Why is that?

00:46:28.245 --> 00:46:29.870
DEREK THOMPSON: So
first of all, hello.

00:46:29.870 --> 00:46:30.953
I didn't see you at first.

00:46:33.479 --> 00:46:36.020
This comes back to an idea in
developmental psychology called

00:46:36.020 --> 00:46:37.997
sensitive periods.

00:46:37.997 --> 00:46:40.580
There are sensitive periods, I
think, for all sorts of tastes.

00:46:40.580 --> 00:46:42.200
For food taste, the
sensitive period

00:46:42.200 --> 00:46:46.780
seems to be between birth
and two, three years old

00:46:46.780 --> 00:46:50.960
that, for example,
broccoli evolved

00:46:50.960 --> 00:46:53.510
to taste bitter and bad.

00:46:53.510 --> 00:46:56.270
But if you feed lots of
broccoli to a newborn,

00:46:56.270 --> 00:46:58.970
you'll have to sort of mix it in
with the applesauce and sugar.

00:46:58.970 --> 00:47:00.760
But they'll grow up
liking broccoli--

00:47:00.760 --> 00:47:04.370
that babies are very neophiliac,
accepting of new things

00:47:04.370 --> 00:47:06.350
when they're very young.

00:47:06.350 --> 00:47:10.340
The sensitive taste for music
seems to be between the teens

00:47:10.340 --> 00:47:12.110
and early to mid 20s.

00:47:12.110 --> 00:47:14.900
By the age of 33,
Spotify suggested,

00:47:14.900 --> 00:47:19.220
people stopped listening
to new songs entirely.

00:47:19.220 --> 00:47:23.750
So by definition, your tastes
have crystallized by your 30s.

00:47:23.750 --> 00:47:24.980
This is one reason why--

00:47:24.980 --> 00:47:26.540
right, the cliche
of my grandmother

00:47:26.540 --> 00:47:30.170
loves Frank Sinatra and
Oscar and Hammerstein.

00:47:30.170 --> 00:47:32.450
It was too late for
her with the Beatles,

00:47:32.450 --> 00:47:37.730
whereas my parents adored Simon
and Garfunkel and Elton John.

00:47:37.730 --> 00:47:40.400
In fact, what you've
seen is that taste

00:47:40.400 --> 00:47:43.010
in people's favorite
music in their 20s

00:47:43.010 --> 00:47:45.290
is so strong that
artists enjoy what

00:47:45.290 --> 00:47:46.810
are called nostalgia bumps--

00:47:46.810 --> 00:47:49.880
that as parents will
get to a certain age

00:47:49.880 --> 00:47:53.750
and be able to teach their
children the kind of music

00:47:53.750 --> 00:47:56.780
from a certain decade,
that band's popularity will

00:47:56.780 --> 00:47:58.220
rise a bit on
streaming networks,

00:47:58.220 --> 00:48:00.680
because kids who grow up under
parents who naturally like

00:48:00.680 --> 00:48:02.510
Simon and Garfunkel
grow up listening

00:48:02.510 --> 00:48:05.590
to a lot of Simon and Garfunkel
and therefore like them.

00:48:05.590 --> 00:48:08.350
The last interesting implication
of this is in politics.

00:48:08.350 --> 00:48:11.660
The political sensitive period
seems to be from mid-20s to--

00:48:11.660 --> 00:48:13.400
I'm sorry, from
mid-teens to late 20s

00:48:13.400 --> 00:48:15.470
as well, really
similar to music.

00:48:15.470 --> 00:48:17.180
So it's kind of
interesting and, I think,

00:48:17.180 --> 00:48:19.470
intuitive that music
taste and political tastes

00:48:19.470 --> 00:48:22.070
are sort of crystallizing
around the same time.

00:48:22.070 --> 00:48:25.940
And this explains a phenomenon
that the right bemoans,

00:48:25.940 --> 00:48:29.570
which is, why do so many
children of conservatives

00:48:29.570 --> 00:48:31.670
grow up becoming liberals?

00:48:31.670 --> 00:48:33.890
And one theory is
that you have children

00:48:33.890 --> 00:48:37.130
who develop a taste
for politics in general

00:48:37.130 --> 00:48:38.900
in their teenage
years, but then go

00:48:38.900 --> 00:48:41.450
to college at, say, University
of Michigan or Northwestern

00:48:41.450 --> 00:48:42.560
or Middlebury.

00:48:42.560 --> 00:48:46.280
And they will be surrounded
by more liberal students.

00:48:46.280 --> 00:48:50.770
And as their ideologies within
politics are crystallizing,

00:48:50.770 --> 00:48:51.830
they'll become liberal.

00:48:51.830 --> 00:48:56.210
So the parents' interest
in politics has screwed,

00:48:56.210 --> 00:48:59.390
you might say, them out of
sharing an ideological bond

00:48:59.390 --> 00:49:00.260
with their child.

00:49:00.260 --> 00:49:01.843
They've developed a
taste for politics

00:49:01.843 --> 00:49:05.060
in a kid who then goes
off to crystallize

00:49:05.060 --> 00:49:07.589
the taste on a liberal campus.

00:49:07.589 --> 00:49:10.130
Basically, the short answer to
your question-- and I'm sorry,

00:49:10.130 --> 00:49:13.130
I just love the topic
of sensitive periods--

00:49:13.130 --> 00:49:16.760
is that we seem to
peak-- our neophilia--

00:49:16.760 --> 00:49:18.680
our interest in
discovering new ideas

00:49:18.680 --> 00:49:20.780
seems to peak at a
certain part of our life.

00:49:20.780 --> 00:49:24.860
And we, somewhat depressingly,
spend the rest of our lives

00:49:24.860 --> 00:49:27.050
playing around with tastes
that have already formed.

